<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-152  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 152.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 26 1990 v4 n8 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OFPP urges increased electronic interchange. (the Office ofFederal Procurement Policy supports electronic data interchange)(Technology) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marsan, Carolyn Duffy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Office of Federal Procurement Policy urges the President'sCouncil on Management Improvement to promote electronic datainterchange (EDI) to reduce paperwork and increase efficiency inthe government procurement process.andP;  OFPP Deputy AssociateAdministrator Neil Lamb told a recent EDI seminar that the officehas asked that procurement process automation be included in thePresident's Management by Objective report and that an interagencyworking group on EDI be established.andP;  PCMI is one of fivepresidential councils formed by President Reagan during his firstterm; it is made up of 23 assistant secretaries for management atdifferent federal agencies and is charged with finding ways toimprove productivity.andP;  The PCMI Systems Committee will discussautomated procurement systems at a meeting in Mar 1990, where itis expected to approve the procurement automation effort andsupport EDI.andP;  Current federal government EDI applications aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationNational GovernmentPlanningGovernment AgencyElectronic Data InterchangeCommunications TechnologyPurchasing SystemsEnhancementsReportsApplicationsMarket AnalysisUnited States. Office of Federal Procurement Policy.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Applications of electronic data interchange in the federalgovernment. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>